    <!-- ════ EQUATION HORIZON (the navigation) ════ -->
    <header class="horizon">
      <p class="label">Our method, in one equation — click a term to open its evidence</p>
      <div class="equation" role="group" aria-label="L of theta equals the integral over the manifold of the squared error-vector norm, plus the ledger term">
        <button type="button" class="term" data-focus="objective" aria-pressed="true"
          data-tip="<b>L(θ)</b> — what we minimize to make a prediction trustworthy: the <em>structured</em> error of a potential θ over all the evidence. The first step to discovering real materials. Click any term to isolate it.">
          L<span class="n">(</span>θ<span class="n">)</span></button>
        <span class="eq-static">=</span>
        <button type="button" class="term" data-focus="manifold"
          data-tip="<b>∫<sub>M</sub> … dμ(γ)</b> — integrate over the error manifold M. The errors live on a thin ribbon (participation ratio <em>1.1–2.0</em>) — structure that makes failure correctable.">
          <span class="intg">∫</span><span class="sub">M</span></button>
        <button type="button" class="term" data-focus="errorvectors"
          data-tip="<b>∇<sub>γ</sub>E(x,θ)</b> — the error-vector field along geodesics γ. Across every MLIP these point the <em>same direction</em> (cos θ &gt; 0.8) — so one correction scales across the materials space.">
          <span class="n">‖</span>∇<span class="sub">γ</span>E<span class="n">(</span>x,θ<span class="n">)</span><span class="n">‖</span><span class="sup">2</span></button>
        <span class="term eq-measure"
          data-tip="<b>dμ(γ)</b> — the measure over geodesics γ. How error is weighted across the ribbon.">
          dμ<span class="n">(</span>γ<span class="n">)</span></span>
        <span class="eq-static">+</span>
        <button type="button" class="term" data-focus="ledger"
          data-tip="<b>Ω(Ξ)</b> — the public record Ξ. Every claim, refutation, and machine-checked theorem, committed and inspectable.">
          Ω<span class="n">(</span>Ξ<span class="n">)</span></button>
      </div>
      <!-- legend / secondary nav for the terms — grouped with the equation -->
      <nav class="legend" aria-label="Equation terms">
        <button type="button" data-focus="objective" aria-pressed="true"><span class="k">L(θ)</span> the mission</button>
        <button type="button" data-focus="manifold"><span class="k">∫ₘ</span> why you can trust it</button>
        <button type="button" data-focus="errorvectors"><span class="k">∇ᵧE</span> why it scales</button>
        <button type="button" data-focus="ledger"><span class="k">Ω(Ξ)</span> trust in the open</button>
      </nav>
    </header>

    <!-- ════ EVIDENCE — resolves in place ════ -->
    <section class="reading" id="evidence" aria-label="Evidence" aria-live="polite">
      <div class="evidence">
        <article class="panel" data-panel="objective" data-active>
          <p class="tag"><span class="dot"></span>L(θ) · the mission</p>
          <h1>Intelligence became abundant. <em>Verified knowledge did not.</em></h1>
          <p>The industry is betting that the smartest model wins. The winning asset is different: a prediction you can <em>check</em> before you commit. AI is learning to design matter, and it already proposes new batteries, catalysts, and chips faster than any lab can test them. A model can be confident and wrong, and finding out which costs years. Lupine builds the check.</p>
          <p class="why">The mathematics is <em>how.</em> The materials are <em>why.</em></p>
          <p class="prov"><span class="live-dot2" aria-hidden="true"></span><span id="prov-objective">computing the manifold live from the committed benchmark…</span></p>
          <div class="routes">
            <a href="https://lupi.live">See it live <span class="ar">→</span></a>
            <a href="https://library.lupine.science">Read the research <span class="ar">→</span></a>
            <a href="https://github.com/alexwelcing/lupine">Audit the code <span class="ar">→</span></a>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="panel" data-panel="manifold">
          <p class="tag"><span class="dot"></span>∫<sub>M</sub> · why you can trust it</p>
          <h2>Predictable failure is <em>correctable</em> failure.</h2>
          <div class="stat"><strong>1.1–2.0</strong><span class="su">the errors move in only ~1–2 directions out of five</span></div>
          <p class="prov"><span class="live-dot2" aria-hidden="true"></span><span id="prov-manifold">…</span></p>
          <p>Across the benchmark potentials we test — classic and AI-driven — the mistakes don't scatter. They line up. And a pattern we can predict is a pattern we can <em>correct</em>: we can flag which predictions to trust before a lab spends a year chasing a dead end.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="panel" data-panel="errorvectors">
          <p class="tag"><span class="dot"></span>∇<sub>γ</sub>E · why it scales</p>
          <h2>Correct it once — <em>accelerate everywhere.</em></h2>
          <div class="stat"><strong>~70%</strong><span class="su">the dominant error directions are shared, so one correction transfers across potentials</span></div>
          <p class="prov"><span class="live-dot2" aria-hidden="true"></span><span id="prov-errorvectors">…</span></p>
          <p>Every model we test leans in a structured way. In most cases, the dominant error direction is similar enough that a single correction scales. Like a room of clocks all running fast: find the offset once, and you can set every one right. One correction, applied across materials.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="panel" data-panel="ledger">
          <p class="tag"><span class="dot"></span>Ω(Ξ) · trust in the open</p>
          <h2>Trust you can <em>check yourself.</em></h2>
          <div class="stat"><strong>0 gaps</strong><span class="su">the core math, checked end to end by computer — not opinion</span></div>
          <p class="prov"><span class="live-dot2" aria-hidden="true"></span><span id="prov-ledger">…</span></p>
          <p>We don't ask anyone to take our word for it. A computer checks our core math the way a spell-checker reads a sentence — every step, nothing skipped. We work in the open, and when one of our own ideas turns out to be wrong, we say so and publish it — <span class="num">3</span> times so far.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ════ LEDGER RAIL (marginalia) ════ -->
    <aside class="rail-ledger" aria-label="Public ledger">
      <div class="rail-head"><span>Public ledger · Ξ</span><span class="h">height <span id="ledger-height">970</span></span></div>
      <ul class="ledger" id="ledger-list">
        <li class="loading">loading open record…</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="rail-note">
        <div class="row"><span class="d wp"></span><span>Working paper in preparation — not yet peer-reviewed. The full record lives in the open repository.</span></div>
        <div class="row"><span class="d mof"></span><span>On the field: MOF-5 · Zn₄O(BDC)₃ — real published crystallography, <a href="/data/mof5_structure.json">drawn from the committed structure</a>.<span class="cite">Li, Eddaoudi, O’Keeffe &amp; Yaghi, Nature 402, 276 (1999) · COD 1516287</span></span></div>
      </div>
    </aside>

  </main>

  <!-- ════ BENEATH THE INSTRUMENT — the substance, one scroll down ════ -->
  <section class="beneath manifesto" aria-label="Why now">
    <p class="b-label">Why now — and why in the open</p>
    <div class="m-grid">
      <p><b>Imagination stopped being the bottleneck.</b> Generative models now propose far more candidate materials than anyone can test.</p>
      <p><b>Simulation stopped being the bottleneck.</b> Machine-learned simulators now screen candidates at software speed. The open question is <em>when to believe them.</em></p>
      <p><b>Belief is the bottleneck.</b> A lab bets a year on a shortlist. A fund bets years on the lab. Which predictions deserve that bet is the question that gates this field, and it is the one we work on. We answer it with proof, in public, so a result checked once can be used by anyone.</p>
    </div>
    <p class="m-place">Our position is specific. Model builders get external verification. Labs get shortlists they can defend. We are <em>the trust layer between the models and the bench,</em> and we publish everything.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="beneath diligence" aria-label="A note on diligence">
    <p class="b-label">A note on diligence</p>
    <div class="dil-body">
      <p>Every deck in this field claims a smarter model. Almost none offers a way to tell a true claim from a confident one. Capital placed on confidence does not fail at the term sheet. It fails years later, at the bench.</p>
      <p>We built this page for diligence. Every figure was computed in your browser after you arrived, from data we commit in public. The core mathematics is machine-checked. Where the record is early, we say so. Do not take our word for any of it. Click a term of the equation above and read the evidence. <em>Checking us takes minutes.</em></p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="beneath" aria-label="What this unlocks">
    <header class="b-head">
      <p class="b-label">What this unlocks</p>
      <h2>The future is made of matter that <em>doesn’t exist yet.</em></h2>
    </header>
    <div class="b-grid">
      <article>
        <h3>Batteries that hold more and degrade slower.</h3>
        <p>Energy storage lives and dies on electrode and electrolyte materials. When a model’s errors are characterized, a lab can trust its shortlist — and spend the year on the ten candidates that matter instead of the thousand that don’t.</p>
        <a href="https://library.lupine.science">Read the research <span class="ar">→</span></a>
      </article>
      <article>
        <h3>Catalysts that make clean industry affordable.</h3>
        <p>From green hydrogen to carbon capture, the cost curve is a materials problem. Correctable simulation means screening chemistries at software speed, with a clear read on when the simulation can be trusted.</p>
        <a href="https://lupi.live">See the instrument <span class="ar">→</span></a>
      </article>
      <article>
        <h3>Frameworks designed for jobs no known material can do.</h3>
        <p>Metal-organic frameworks can be built atom-by-atom for capture, storage and sensing. The crystal drawn above is real, published crystallography. Our prospectus for makeable frameworks is in the notebook below.</p>
        <a href="/articles/from-fantasy-frameworks-to-makeable-materials/">Read the prospectus <span class="ar">→</span></a>
      </article>
    </div>

    <div class="feature-series" aria-label="Climate partnerships series">
      <p class="b-label">Climate partnerships series</p>
      <div class="series-head">
        <h2>Beyond carbon: the error geometry of environmental materials.</h2>
        <p>Five articles trace the same under-coordination error from CO₂ capture to water, air, methane, refrigerants, critical minerals, PFAS, and cement — and show how a single correction layer changes what labs can trust.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="series-cards">
        <a href="/articles/beyond-carbon-the-error-geometry-of-environmental-materials/">
          <img src="/articles/beyond-carbon-the-error-geometry-of-environmental-materials/hero.jpg" alt="" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="640" height="360">
          <span class="d8">July 16, 2026 · Series intro</span>
          <h3>Beyond Carbon</h3>
          <p>The one geometry that connects every environmental-materials campaign.</p>
        </a>
        <a href="/articles/water-and-air-correcting-the-molecules-we-drink-and-breathe/">
          <img src="/articles/water-and-air-correcting-the-molecules-we-drink-and-breathe/hero.jpg" alt="" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="640" height="360">
          <span class="d8">July 16, 2026</span>
          <h3>Water and Air</h3>
          <p>Correcting the molecules we drink and breathe.</p>
        </a>
        <a href="/articles/methane-and-refrigerants-cutting-the-non-co2-climate-forcers/">
          <img src="/articles/methane-and-refrigerants-cutting-the-non-co2-climate-forcers/hero.jpg" alt="" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="640" height="360">
          <span class="d8">July 16, 2026</span>
